Attributes and Methods in Python

In Python OOP, classes and objects contain two important things:

Attributes → Data or properties
Methods → Actions or behaviors

1. Attributes in Python
Definition

Attributes are variables inside a class or object.
They store information related to the object.

Real-Life Example

Car Object
| Attribute | Value |
| --------- | ----- |
| Brand     | BMW   |
| Color     | Black |
| Speed     | 200   |
These properties are attributes.

Types of Attributes
| Type               | Meaning               |
| ------------------ | --------------------- |
| Instance Attribute | Belongs to object     |
| Class Attribute    | Shared by all objects |

A) Instance Attributes

Instance attributes are created separately for each object.
Usually defined inside:
  __init__()

Example
class Student:

    def __init__(self, name, age):
        self.name = name
        self.age = age

s1 = Student("Rahul", 20)

print(s1.name)
print(s1.age)

Explanation

Part	Meaning
| Part      | Meaning            |
| --------- | ------------------ |
| self.name | Instance attribute |
| self.age  | Instance attribute |
| Rahul     | Value of name      |
| 20        | Value of age       |


Each object gets its own values.

Memory Understanding

If we create:

s1 = Student("Rahul", 20)
s2 = Student("Aman", 22)

Then:

| Object | Attributes |
| ------ | ---------- |
| s1     | Rahul, 20  |
| s2     | Aman, 22   |


Both objects store separate data.

B) Class Attributes

Class attributes are shared by all objects.
Defined directly inside class.

Example
class Student:

    school = "ABC School"

    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name

s1 = Student("Rahul")
s2 = Student("Aman")

print(s1.school)
print(s2.school)
Explanation

school belongs to class, not individual object.

All objects use same value.

Difference Between Instance and Class Attributes
| Instance Attribute     | Class Attribute           |
| ---------------------- | ------------------------- |
| Unique for each object | Shared by all objects     |
| Defined in constructor | Defined directly in class |
| Uses `self`            | No `self` needed          |
| Separate memory        | Common memory             |

Accessing Attributes

Syntax
object.attribute

Example
print(s1.name)

Modifying Attributes
s1.name = "Amit"
Attribute value changes.

Deleting Attributes
del s1.name

Deletes attribute from object.

Built-in Attribute Functions
| Function  | Purpose                |
| --------- | ---------------------- |
| getattr() | Get attribute value    |
| setattr() | Set attribute value    |
| hasattr() | Check attribute exists |
| delattr() | Delete attribute       |

Example
print(hasattr(s1, "name"))

2. Methods in Python
Definition

Methods are functions inside a class.
They define object behavior.

Real-Life Example
Car
| Method       | Action          |
| ------------ | --------------- |
| start()      | Starts car      |
| stop()       | Stops car       |
| accelerate() | Increases speed |

Syntax of Method
class Demo:

    def method_name(self):
        pass

Example of Method
class Student:

    def show(self):
        print("Hello Student")

s1 = Student()

s1.show()

Understanding self ------

self refers to current object.
It helps access:
  Attributes
  Other methods
inside class.

Types of Methods
| Type            | Explanation                |
| --------------- | -------------------------- |
| Instance Method | Works with object data     |
| Class Method    | Works with class data      |
| Static Method   | Independent utility method |

A) Instance Method

Most common method type.

Uses:

self
Object attributes
Example
class Student:

    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name

    def display(self):
        print(self.name)

B) Class Method
Works with class attributes.

Uses decorator:
@classmethod

Uses cls instead of self.

Example
class Student:

    school = "ABC"

    @classmethod
    def show_school(cls):
        print(cls.school)

C) Static Method

Independent method.
Does not use:
  self
  cls

Uses decorator:
@staticmethod

Example
class Math:

    @staticmethod
    def add(a, b):
        print(a + b)

Difference Between Methods
| Method Type     | Uses                 |
| --------------- | -------------------- |
| Instance Method | Object data          |
| Class Method    | Class data           |
| Static Method   | General utility work |

Calling Methods
Syntax
object.method()

Example
s1.display()

Complete Example
class Employee:

    company = "TCS"

    def __init__(self, name, salary):
        self.name = name
        self.salary = salary

    def show(self):
        print(self.name)
        print(self.salary)

    @classmethod
    def company_name(cls):
        print(cls.company)

    @staticmethod
    def greet():
        print("Welcome")

e1 = Employee("Rahul", 50000)

e1.show()

Employee.company_name()

Employee.greet()

Output
Rahul
50000
TCS
Welcome

Important Difference Between Attributes and Methods
| Attributes           | Methods                    |
| -------------------- | -------------------------- |
| Store data           | Perform actions            |
| Variables            | Functions                  |
| Represent properties | Represent behavior         |
| Example: name, age   | Example: display(), show() |


Important Points to Remember
| Point                          | Explanation                   |
| ------------------------------ | ----------------------------- |
| Attributes store object data   | Methods define behavior       |
| `self` accesses current object | Important in instance methods |
| Class attributes shared by all | Instance attributes unique    |
| Methods can access attributes  | Through self                  |

Short Summary

Attributes are variables that store object data.
Methods are functions that define object behavior.
Together, they form the foundation of OOP in Python.
